# Group Proposal

Victor Wu (vwu24@calpoly.edu)
Jared Moy (jmoy02@calpoly.edu)
Avery Robinson (avrobins@calpoly.edu)
Daniel Pineda (dpined04@calpoly.edu)

The goal of this project is to build a relational database-driven application that moves away from static recipe
text and toward a dynamic, interconnected "food graph." Unlike basic cookbook apps, this system treats ingredients
as independent entities with their own attributes, allowing for advanced querying and logic. The core functionality
focuses on a "Smart Swap" engine that uses self-referencing tables to suggest substitutions based on dietary needs
or missing pantry items.

By utilizing a relational structure, the app can handle complex many-to-many relationships between recipes and
ingredients, while also mapping flavor profiles like "umami" or "zesty" across the entire library. This setup
ensures data integrity—meaning a change to an ingredient’s allergen status automatically updates every recipe
it touches. For the final deliverable, the project will demonstrate how normalized database design can solve
practical problems like automatic unit conversion and real-time recipe filtering.
